            <section class="prose text-sm">
              <h2>How this hard money loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for real estate investors who use hard
                money or private money to fund fix-and-flip, BRRRR, or bridge
                deals. It combines a
                <strong>hard money payment calculator</strong> with a
                <strong>deal analyzer</strong> so you can see:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Loan amount based on LTV / LTC or ARV</li>
                <li>Interest-only monthly payment and total interest</li>
                <li>Points and closing costs</li>
                <li>Cash to close and total cash invested</li>
                <li>
                  Projected profit, margin, and ROI (including annualized ROI)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Loan amount calculation</h3>
              <p>The calculator supports three common hard money structures:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Purchase price (LTV):</strong> loan = LTV × purchase
                  price
                </li>
                <li><strong>ARV-based:</strong> loan = LTV × ARV</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total cost (LTC):</strong> loan = LTV × (purchase
                  price + rehab)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The loan amount is capped so it never exceeds the total project
                cost (purchase + rehab). Any rehab not covered by the lender is
                treated as
                <strong>unfunded rehab</strong> that you must pay in cash.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Loan amount</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( P \) = purchase price, \( R \) = rehab budget, \( A \)
                  = ARV, \( L \) = LTV/LTC (as decimal).<br />
                  If basis = purchase: \( \text{Loan} = \min(L \cdot P,\; P + R)
                  \)<br />
                  If basis = ARV: \( \text{Loan} = \min(L \cdot A,\; P + R)
                  \)<br />
                  If basis = total cost: \( \text{Loan} = \min(L \cdot (P +
                  R),\; P + R) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Interest-only payment and total interest</h3>
              <p>
                Most hard money loans are <strong>interest-only</strong> during
                the term, with the principal repaid when you sell or refinance.
                The monthly payment is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Monthly payment</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( L_0 \) = loan amount, \( r \) = annual interest rate
                  (decimal).<br />
                  \( \text{Monthly payment} = L_0 \times \dfrac{r}{12} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Total interest over your <em>holding period</em> (not
                necessarily the full loan term) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Total interest</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( m \) = holding period in months.<br />
                  \( \text{Total interest} = \text{Monthly payment} \times m \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Points, closing costs, and cash to close</h3>
              <p>
                Points are an upfront fee charged by the lender, expressed as a
                percentage of the loan amount. For example, 2 points on a
                \$200,000 loan is \$4,000.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Points cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( p \) = points (as decimal).<br />
                  \( \text{Points cost} = L_0 \times p \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Cash to close includes your down payment, points, other closing
                costs, and any rehab not funded by the lender:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Cash to close</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Down payment} = P - \text{Loan portion applied to
                  purchase} \)<br />
                  \( \text{Unfunded rehab} = \max(0,\; R - \text{Loan portion
                  applied to rehab}) \)<br />
                  \( \text{Cash to close} = \text{Down payment} + \text{Unfunded
                  rehab} + \text{Points} + \text{Other closing costs} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Carrying costs and total cash invested</h3>
              <p>
                To get a realistic ROI, you need to include
                <strong>carrying costs</strong> such as taxes, insurance,
                utilities, HOA, and maintenance. The calculator multiplies your
                monthly carrying costs by the holding period and adds them to
                your cash invested:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Total cash invested</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( C_m \) = monthly carrying costs, \( m \) = holding
                  months.<br />
                  \( \text{Carrying costs} = C_m \times m \)<br />
                  \( \text{Total cash invested} = \text{Cash to close} +
                  \text{Carrying costs} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Profit, margin, and ROI</h3>
              <p>
                By default, the calculator assumes you sell at the ARV and pay
                selling costs (agent commissions, seller closing costs, etc.) as
                a percentage of the sale price.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Profit and ROI</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( S \) = sale price (default = ARV), \( s \) = selling
                  cost % (decimal).<br />
                  \( \text{Selling costs} = S \times s \)<br />
                  \( \text{Total project cost} = P + R + \text{Closing costs} +
                  \text{Total interest} + \text{Carrying costs} \)<br />
                  \( \text{Profit} = S - \text{Selling costs} - \text{Total
                  project cost} \)<br />
                  \( \text{Profit margin} = \dfrac{\text{Profit}}{S} \)<br />
                  \( \text{ROI} = \dfrac{\text{Profit}}{\text{Total cash
                  invested}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                To make deals comparable across different holding periods, we
                also compute an <strong>annualized ROI</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Annualized ROI</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( R \) = ROI (decimal), \( m \) = holding months.<br />
                  \( \text{Annualized ROI} = (1 + R)^{12/m} - 1 \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Tips for using hard money effectively</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stress-test your deal:</strong> Try lower ARV, higher
                  rehab, or longer holding periods to see how sensitive your
                  profit is.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare lenders:</strong> Small differences in rate
                  and points can significantly change your cash to close and
                  ROI.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mind your leverage:</strong> Higher LTV reduces cash
                  to close but increases risk and monthly payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Plan exit strategies:</strong> Know whether you’ll
                  sell, refinance into a long-term loan, or hold as a rental.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is a hard money loan?</h3>
              <p>
                A hard money loan is a short-term, asset-based real estate loan.
                Instead of focusing mainly on your income and credit, the lender
                looks at the
                <strong>property value, rehab plan, and exit strategy</strong>.
                These loans are common for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Fix-and-flip projects</li>
                <li>
                  Bridge financing between purchase and long-term financing
                </li>
                <li>Quick closings where traditional banks are too slow</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>
                How is a hard money loan different from a conventional mortgage?
              </h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Term:</strong> Hard money is usually 6–18 months;
                  conventional is 15–30 years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Payments:</strong> Hard money is often interest-only;
                  conventional is amortizing principal + interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rates & fees:</strong> Hard money has higher rates and
                  more points, but funds faster and with more flexibility.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Underwriting:</strong> Hard money focuses on the deal
                  and collateral; conventional focuses on borrower income and
                  credit.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>What LTV do hard money lenders use?</h3>
              <p>
                Many lenders cap loans at
                <strong>70–80% of purchase price</strong> or
                <strong>65–75% of ARV</strong>. Some also use
                <strong>loan-to-cost (LTC)</strong> based on purchase plus
                rehab. This calculator lets you model all three.
              </p>

              <h3>Are the results guaranteed?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is for
                <strong>estimation and education only</strong>. Actual terms,
                fees, and underwriting vary by lender and market. Always verify
                numbers with your lender, contractor, and real estate
                professionals before committing to a deal.
              </p>
